Regression task

dfii <- df %>% 
  mutate(y = boot::logit( (response - 0) / (100 - 0) ) ) %>% 
  select(R, G, B, 
         Lightness, Saturation, Hue,
         y)

Fitting models using lm()

Intercept-only model

mod1 <- lm(y ~ 1, data = dfii)

Categorical variables only - linear additive

mod2 <- lm(y ~ Lightness + Saturation, data = dfii)

Continuous variables only - linear additive

mod3 <- lm(y ~ R + G + B + Hue, data = dfii)

All categorical and continuous variables - linear additive

mod4 <- lm(y ~ R + G + B + Lightness + Saturation + Hue, data = dfii)

Interaction of categorical inputs with all continuous inputs main effects

#mod5 <- lm(y ~ (Lightness + Saturation) * (R + G + B + Hue), data = dfii)
mod5 <- lm(y ~ Lightness:R + Lightness:G + Lightness:B + Saturation:R + Saturation:G + Saturation:B + Hue:R + Hue:G + Hue:B, data = dfii)

Add categorical inputs to all main effect and all pairwise interactions of continuous inputs

#mod6 <- lm(y ~ R * G * B * Lightness * Saturation * Hue, data = dfii)
mod6 <- lm(y ~ R + G + B + Lightness + Saturation + Hue + R:Lightness + R:Saturation + R:Hue + G:Lightness + G:Saturation + G:Hue + B:Lightness + B:Saturation + B:Hue, data = dfii)

Interaction of the categorical inputs with all main effect and all pairwise interactions of continuous inputs

mod7 <- lm(y ~ Lightness + Saturation + Hue + Lightness:R + Lightness:G + Lightness:B + Saturation:R + Saturation:G + Saturation:B + Hue:R + Hue:G + Hue:B, data = dfii)

Model with basis functions of your choice

using cubic spline basis function for R variable

library(splines)
mod8 <- lm(y ~ ns(R, df = 4) + G + B + Lightness + Saturation + Hue, data = dfii)

using exponential transformation for G variable

mod9 <- lm(y ~ R + exp(G) + B + Lightness + Saturation + Hue, data = dfii)

using interaction between cubic spline basis function for R variable and Saturation variable

mod10 <- lm(y ~ ns(R, df = 4) + G + B + Lightness + Saturation + Hue + ns(R, df = 4):Saturation, data = dfii)

Model 10 is the best, because they have the highest r.squared value.

Visualize the coefficient summaries for your top 3 models

coefplot::coefplot(mod10)

coefplot::coefplot(mod7)

coefplot::coefplot(mod6)

Comparing the coefficient summaries of the top 3 models can give us insights into which inputs are important. We can look at the sign and magnitude of the coefficients to determine the direction and strength of the relationship between the inputs and the output. A positive coefficient indicates a positive relationship, while a negative coefficient indicates a negative relationship. The magnitude of the coefficient represents the strength of the relationship.

summary_mod10 <- mod10 %>%
  coefplot::coefplot(sort = "magnitude", plot = FALSE) %>%
  tibble::as_tibble() %>%
  filter((HighOuter > 0 & LowOuter > 0) | (HighOuter < 0 & LowOuter < 0))
